        "newspaperPageNumber":"25",
        "trailText":"FTSE 100 company says hostile approach from private equity group was highly opportunistic and undervalued the business<br />",
        "headline":"G4S rejects £1.55bn Charterhouse offer for cash solutions business",
        "body":"<p>G4S, the world's biggest security group, has rejected a £1.55bn offer for its cash transportation business from a private equity firm, dismissing it as \"highly opportunistic\".</p><p>The company  at the centre of controversies including the 2012 Olympics security fiasco, said the hostile approach from Charterhouse Capital Partners \"fundamentally undervalues\" the business.</p><p>It added that the cash solutions business, which accounted for 18% of group turnover in 2012 and uses high security vehicles to transport cash for banks and retailers, was an important part of the group's future.</p><p>G4S said in a statement on Monday it had received the offer on 22 October and had firmly rejected it \"following due consideration, with the assistance of financial advisers\".</p><p>\"G4S is committed to invest in its core businesses, including cash solutions, which have strong opportunities for sustainable profitable growth.</p><p>\"The cash solutions business is integral to G4S's operations and strategic plans,\" the company said.</p><p>Threadneedle, which owns around 1.3% of G4S, said the company was right to reject the offer from Charterhouse.</p><p>Chris Kinder, UK equity fund manager at Threadneedle, said: \"We are supportive of the G4S management stance on the Charterhouse bid. The offered price of £1.55bn is relatively low for a strategically important and strongly performing part of the company. The rejection is consistent with G4S' strategy to sell underperforming businesses – but cash solutions is not one of them.\"</p><p>The FTSE 100 company laid out its case for keeping the business, which also builds and manages high security cash centres for customers, sorts notes for use in ATM machines, offers counterfeit detection and manages ATMs.</p><p>It said that cash in circulation in both its developed and emerging markets was growing strongly and emphasised its long-term contracts with blue chip, global customers.</p><p>The offer comes as the company attempts to rebuild its reputation following the London Olympics security shambles, when it failed to provide sufficient numbers of staff to guard the Games.</p><p>Former G4S chief executive Nick Buckles survived the initial fallout from the Olympics contract, which ultimately cost G4S £88m, but <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/may/21/g4s-nick-buckles-quits\" title=\"\">quit in May in the wake of a profit warning</a>.</p><p>He had worked at the company for 28 years, and left with a total financial package of around £16m, including pension and shares.</p><p>G4S, along with rival Serco, was also accused earlier in the year of overcharging the taxpayer for electronically tagging criminals who were dead, in prison or never tagged in the first place.</p><p>News of the approach from Charterhouse came as it emerged a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/28/g4s-run-prison-south-africa-investigation\" title=\"\">South African prison run by G4S was under investigation</a> for allegedly using forced injections and electric shock treatment to subdue inmates.</p><p>The latest allegations relating to Mangaung Correctional Centre near Bloemfontein follow a year-long investigation by the <a href=\"http://witsjusticeproject.com/about/\" title=\"\">Wits Justice Project</a>, part of the University of Witwatersrand journalism department.</p><p>G4S denies any acts of assault or torture.</p><p>A spokesman said: \"G4S staff at Manguang Correctional Services do not have access to medication nor do they administer medication. All medical decisions for inmates are handled and addressed by independent certified medical staff, who may diagnose certain conditions, including any possible mental disorders, and prescribe medication in accordance with the relevant condition.</p><p>\"We can confirm that we do not use any form of torture or shock treatment. There is an active and independent inspection regime in place at the prison – 365 days per year – and there have never been any allegations or concerns regarding anything of this nature.</p><p>\"We take such allegations very seriously and will be launching our own investigations into the matter. It would not be appropriate to comment further at this stage.\"</p><p>Meanwhile analysts backed the company's decision to reject the approach from Charterhouse.</p><p>Robert Plant, analyst at JP Morgan, said: \"We think G4S was right to reject the bid, on both valuation and strategic grounds. In particular, we believe that the UK cash business will start to improve due to the turnaround strategy enacted this year and the whole of the cash division will benefit as interest rates rise, so G4S could be selling at the bottom of the cycle.\"</p><p></p><p>New chief executive Ashley Almanza, who joined G4S as chief financial officer just three weeks before Buckles' departure was announced, said in August the company would divest a number of non-core businesses.</p><p>He said the company was working on systems and processes to improve efficiency and risk management, and would be restructuring a number of businesses to make them more competitive and able to deliver improved margins.</p><p>G4S had a turnover of around £7.3bn in 2012, excluding the Olympics contract, with operations in more than 120 countries and more than 620,000 staff.</p><p>The biggest part of the group is the provision of security solutions, including manned security for companies, which accounted for 59% of turnover in 2012.</p><p>Government secure solutions, including work in the care and justice sectors and border protection, is the second largest part of the group at 23% of turnover in 2012, followed by cash solutions at 18%.</p><p>Charterhouse did not respond to requests for comment.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421103960|2013-11-05T11:03:51Z|b508ef1bef68cdac1edd27a3b0516a8ae7426091 -->",
